laitoin tänään kesätyöhakemuksen  norjalaiseen hotelliin ja toisen hakemuksen au pairiksi irlantiin. Se au pair juttu ois aika mahtava homma. matkat ja majoitus sekä ruuat maksetaan ja lisäks viel palkkaa. kaiken lisäks niille lapsille pitää kuulemma puhua suomea, kun perhe on kaksikielinen ja lasten suomentaitoa pitäs parantaa. HELPPOA RAHAA. ei tarvii kuulemma ees siivota.
en kyllä varmana saa noin hyvää paikkaa :p

" I'll be working with Amanda Palmer on the WHO KILLED AMANDA PALMER Book for the next couple of days. It's a book of photos of her with occasional words by me, which are currently being written."

- Neil Gaiman on his blog

So. Two of my favorite people are making a book together! How cool is that? For you who don't know (and probably don't care, but i'll tell you anyway) Amanda Palmer is the awesomely incredible singer of The Dresden Dolls, whom i adore, and Neil Gaiman is a demigod the writer of cult comic Sandman and numerous  fantasy books (Nevermore, Stardust). I had no idea they even knew each other, it's so weird when you notice how small the world is, really.

Amanda has a Europe tour coming up, and if she's coming to Finland I will so be there. I love this song <3

Also, one of my favorite fanfiction writers have published a book that i have to somehow get my hands on. Fortunately, although it's just been published in America and I was certain it would be hard to get it from Finland,  Akateeminen Kirjakauppa has answered my prayers. yet again.

I feel like starting some incredible huge artistic project, but i think i'tll have to wait until i finish all my other stuff AND i should be starting on my final showcase thingy for school, witch will probably be a big french court dress. I already have the fabrics and basic idea, something like this, but in beige and light blue. Another dress i'm going to make someday in the far future when i'm not so busy, is Ms. Lovett's dress from Sweeney Todd. I dont know wich one yet, but i loved all of her costumes.

I've been stressed out all week because I thought that we had to get our unfinished assingments done by this friday, and then on thursday the teacher says we have one more week to do them...!
My brain has been on severe explosion danger zone the whole week for no reason, thanks a lot.

I still have a huge headache, though I did get to have some awesomeness on friday, when I was selling band merchendise for Incredible Nothing (a finnish indie band) at Vernissa club in Tikkurila with
mentalpanic
.
They let us in through the BACK DOOR and we got to hang around while they put up the gear and did soundcheck. We got free entrance & free FOOD witch i find really odd, cause FOOD & GIG just don't go together in my world...
It was nice. Really nice.
And the drummer Teppo was so sweet, he helped us with the stuff and made sure we got fed and just was a really great guy. Hopefully we'll get to do it again sometime soon. :)

O.O

I can hear the roaring crowds, asking "What the hell have you been doing, instead of updating for all this time!?!".
Well, actually I've been fighting for world order and peace, which is to say I've been sitting on my lazy ass, doing everything you can possibly do on the computer, except updating my livejournal. Is that a good answer? I think it is.

I think there was a point to this post, let me find it...
Ah! It was the fact that I will probably be spending less and less time on my lazy ass, because:
1. My two hobbies are starting again; being incredibly artistic in a crowd, on tuesday evenings and torturing a cat guitar under supervision also on tuesday evenings.
2. I will be helping my mom with a english club for under-10-year-olds on mondays (which would be fine, but I was informed that I'll be having two of them without my dear mother, just me and the little devils. oh joy).
 Also i'm in a fulltime panic of "whatthehellamIgonnawear!!!!1" because of the Tokyo Dance Night next month. I just bought new dread locks to attach to my hair, they're light blue and wonderful (thank you

It was the most perfect day of my life. We went to Helsinki by bus and arrived at the icehall at about 5.20pm or something. People were sitting around and there didnt seem to be any kind of queue, so we just sat on some stairs. When I think about it now the time went so fast! they opened the doors at 7.00pm and we waited around a bit so it wouldn't be so crowded. when inside we went to buy t-shirts and the crowd was pretty bad. I bought a pink one with the text "Placebo" and "someone call the ambulance there's gonna be an accident", it was 25e. Then I had to stay and wait because they didn't have the badges I wanted to buy for a friend, and kept saying they would be there any minute. So I was pressed against the fence for about 20 minutes and there was this crewmember woman  who spoke english and pushed the fences back when they were being pushed too close and it was pretty horrible but you know... It wouldn't be a proper gig if at some point you weren't being trapped in an enormous pushing crowd an all. Well the badges didn't come, so I went back to my friends and we went to look for our places, which were fucking awesome by the way (A2 row 4 seat 110). We could see the whole stage all the time and the only problem was standing up and jumping, 'cause there was a serious threat of falling down on the people sitting in the next row... Then I was an idiot and left my bag on the seat to go find someting to drink (you couldn't bring the drinks inside the hall) and when I tried to go back in the hall the security woman wouldn't let me in without my ticket witch was in my bag. Fortunately (I probably looked so miserable) she let me in when i explained it to her. The supporting band (Manboy) had just started to play and they were pretty good except they had some problems with the instruments at one point, poor guys. XD Weell then they announced that Placebo was coming onstage in a few moments. I grabbed my friends hand as the lights went out and I can't describe the feeling when Steve came out and then Steff and then Brian and I was so overwhelmed and happy and aaagh! Brian was wearing a collarshirt and a vest and Steff had a collarshirt and a tie and they looked so gorgeous (and brian had hair, yay for that). I was in a haze the whole time so I don't even remember all the songs they played except they were all good. After the few first songs me and one of my friends stood up and I was amased at how few of the people actually stood in the sitting audience. I thought they were all gonna go wild, I mean it's Placebo, they haven't been here for 10 years, c'mon people! But in a sense it was good, 'cause there weren't many people standing and Steff came to our side of the stage and we were jumping and waving and he waved at us!!!! God I still can't believe it. And at one point Brian apologised for the band not being in Finland for "ten fucking years!" and it was so great. And they played Special K and the crowd sang the "padapapapadadada". I've never been to gig like that one and it was something so special (as you can no doubt see from my rather GODDAMN LONG description). The whole evening I had this great feeling of accomplishment and serenity and happines. The Placebo effect.

Setlist:
Infra-Red,Because I Want you,Meds,Drag,Space Monkey,Soulmates,I Know,STSG,Follow The Cops Back Home,EYEM ,Special Needs,One Of A Kind,
WYIN,Bionic,Blind,Special K,The Bitter End

Encore:
Running Up That Hill,Taste In Men,Twenty Years.
